# Ship to GitHub + Lovable (mandatory)

**This repo overrides generic “don’t commit unless asked.”** Shipping is part of “done.”

**Owner workflow:** Cursor ships → GitHub `main` **+** `feature/service-library-nav` (Lovable sync branch) → **you Publish in Lovable → hard refresh**

Lovable watches **`feature/service-library-nav`**, not `main`. `npm run ship` mirrors `main` to that branch automatically.

## Division of responsibility (permanent)

| Who | Does |
|-----|------|
| **Cursor (agent)** | Always `npm run ship` — commit + push to `main` + mirror to `feature/service-library-nav`. Never leave work local-only. |
| **You (owner)** | **Lovable → Publish** (+ approve migrations if prompted) → hard refresh. **No manual git** — no commit, push, or branch work on your side. |

No pull requests unless you explicitly ask for review first.

## After every implementation (UI fix, feature, refactor, docs+code)

1. **Ensure you are on `main`** (`git checkout main && git pull origin main` if needed).
2. **Run `npm run ship`** with a clear message and changed file paths:
   ```bash
   npm run ship -- "fix(course-finder): remove horizontal scroll" -- src/pages/CourseFinder.tsx
   ```
3. **If ship is unavailable**, commit and push yourself — never leave work local-only:
   ```bash
   git add <files> && git commit -m "…" && git push origin main
   ```
4. **Verify push succeeded** before saying anything is deployed:
   ```bash
   git fetch origin && git rev-parse HEAD origin/main origin/feature/service-library-nav
   git log origin/feature/service-library-nav -1 --oneline
   ```

## UI fixes — never stop at “fixed locally”

After UI/page/component changes (`src/pages/**`, `src/components/**`, CSS/theme):

- **Always** run `npm run ship` in the same turn.
- **Always** include Lovable steps in your closing message (see below).
- Do **not** ask “want me to ship?” or “say the word to push.”

## Only skip shipping when

- User explicitly says do not ship / commit / push, or
- There are zero code changes, or
- Pre-commit tests fail — fix first, then ship without re-asking.

## Never do this

- Finish work while files are still uncommitted or unpushed.
- Tell the user to sync Lovable when GitHub has no new commit.
- Ask whether to push for routine CRM/UI work.
- **Ask for approval before commit/push** — owner has pre-authorized auto-ship; run `npm run ship` (or commit+push) without prompting.
- Imply code is live when it is only on the local machine.

## Closing message (required after every ship)

```
✓ On GitHub main: <commit hash> — <one-line summary>
✓ Lovable branch feature/service-library-nav: <same hash>

YOUR ACTION (you — no git):
1. Lovable → Publish (approve pending migrations if any)
2. Hard refresh (Cmd+Shift+R)
```

If migrations or edge functions changed, add: see `docs/LOVABLE_PUBLISH_CHECKLIST.md`.

## PRs

- **Default:** push direct to `main` (no PR).
- **Exception:** user says “open a PR” or “don’t push to main yet”.
